{
  "answer": "In Iqbal's *Sair-e-Falak* (\"Journey through the Heavens\"), the speaker enjoys a literal cosmic voyage with Imagination as companion, ascending past the stars and \"beyond the ring of dusk and dawn\" to escape the solar system entirely.[^1] This marks a transcendent breakthrough into the wider universe, followed by visions of paradisiacal delights and a reimagined Hell.\n\nThe speaker of *The Wanderer*—the \"earth-stepper,\" an exile contemplating earthly ruin—achieves a cosmic vision through meditative wisdom, perceiving how \"this middle-earth each and every day droops and decays\" under the Shaper's decree and the Fates' changes, leaving behind only empty giant-works amid storms and blizzards.[^2] He surveys a \"ghostly\" waste of wealth, halls, and humanity, all loaned and fleeting beneath the heavens.\n\nIqbal's speaker is given more to see: not just earthly transience, but paradises, hells, and celestial expanses beyond our system.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, \"Sair-e-Falak\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/18-sair-e-falak/translation/#p-829290).\n\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, \"The Wanderer\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc).",
